abstract = {Distant star-forming galaxies show a correlation between their star-formation rates (SFR) and stellar masses, and this has deep implications for galaxy formation. Here, we present a study on the evolution of the slope and scatter of the SFR{\$}-{\$}stellar mass relation for galaxies at {\$}3.5\backslashleq z\backslashleq 6.5{\$} using multi-wavelength photometry in GOODS-S from the Cosmic Assembly Near-infrared Deep Extragalactic Legacy Survey (CANDELS) and Spitzer Extended Deep Survey. We describe an updated, Bayesian spectral-energy distribution fitting method that incorporates effects of nebular line emission, star-formation histories that are constant or rising with time, and different dust attenuation prescriptions (starburst and Small Magellanic Cloud). From {\$}z{\$}=6.5 to {\$}z{\$}=3.5 star-forming galaxies in CANDELS follow a nearly unevolving correlation between stellar mass and SFR that follows SFR {\$}\backslashsim{\$} {\$}M{\_}\backslashstar{\^{}}\backslashalpha{\$} with {\$}\backslashalpha = 0.54 \backslashpm 0.16{\$} at {\$}z\backslashsim 6{\$} and {\$}0.70 \backslashpm 0.21{\$} at {\$}z\backslashsim 4{\$}. This evolution requires a star-formation history that increases with decreasing redshift (on average, the SFRs of individual galaxies rise with time). The measured scatter in the SFR{\$}-{\$}stellar mass relation is tight, {\$}\backslashsigma(\backslashlog \backslashmathrm{\{}SFR{\}}/\backslashmathrm{\{}M{\}}{\_}\backslashodot{\$} yr{\$}{\^{}}{\{}-1{\}}){\textless} 0.3 -{\$}0.4 dex, for galaxies with {\$}\backslashlog M{\_}\backslashstar/\backslashmathrm{\{}M{\}}{\_}\backslashodot {\textgreater} 9{\$} dex. Assuming that the SFR is tied to the net gas inflow rate (SFR {\$}\backslashsim{\$} {\$}\backslashdot{\{}M{\}}{\_}\backslashmathrm{\{}gas{\}}{\$}), then the scatter in the gas inflow rate is also smaller than 0.3{\$}-{\$}0.4 dex for star-forming galaxies in these stellar mass and redshift ranges, at least when averaged over the timescale of star-formation. We further show that the implied star-formation history of objects selected on the basis of their co-moving number densities is consistent with the evolution in the SFR{\$}-{\$}stellar mass relation.},
